  "answer": "The critic misreads the forbidden case. The case states that analysis of remains from destruction layers shows no evidence of a novel pathogen and that all observed pathologies are endemic or trauma-related. This observation is entirely compatible with the mechanism, not logically incompatible. The mechanism posits a highly virulent pathogen that kills rapidly—before skeletal lesions can develop—and targets the soft-tissue administrative population whose bodies, in the chaos of opportunistic burning and secondary occupation, would not necessarily be interred in archaeologically visible mass graves within the destruction layers themselves. Endemic pathologies and trauma in the destruction-layer remains are precisely what one would expect if those remains belong to the opportunistic invaders or the final defenders who died by violence, not to the primary plague victims. The forbidden case is therefore not a concrete observation that could realistically falsify the mechanism, because the mechanism does not predict that the pathogen’s victims will be found as bioarchaeologically identifiable skeletons in the destruction layers; it predicts their rapid death and removal or cremation in the collapse sequence, leaving no diagnostic skeletal signature in that specific context."
